Strain based fatigue analysis can account for local plastic deformation. This method is suited for low cycle and high cycle fatigue.

This calculates a safety factor based on the method of constant stress ratio (R) or the method of constant mean stress (M). Note that this is different than the safety factors calculated with the stress or strain based methods.

Stress based fatigue analysis assumes that the stress remains in the elastic region of the material. No correction is made for plasticity. Therefore, this method is suited only for high cycle fatigue (more than 100000 cycles).

The angle size depends on the material, machine, and process settings. The default size of 45Ã‚Â° works well for most additive processes.

Specifies a process that builds the part by adding material layer on layer; also called 3D printing.
Select Additive to generate outcomes showing the design problem solved with that manufacturing method in mind. Select one or more printing build directions (X, Y, Z) to control how the part is oriented on the build plate. Each selected build direction generates a separate set of outcomes. Before manufacturing, outcomes may require modifications for a specific additive process such as SLS or FDM.
Specifies the manufacturing constraints for the design process.
Available options include: Unrestricted, Additive, and Milling. You can select all options and compare outcomes generated for each option.
Outcomes are generated for each manufacturing option that you select.

To include additive constraints, select Additive and specify the Overhang Angle and Minimum Thickness. To include milling constraints, select Milling and specify the Tool Direction, Minimum Tool Diameter, Tool Shoulder Length, and Head Diameter. To avoid manufacturing constraints during the design process, select Unrestricted.

Estimates manufacturing costs for the final iteration of outcomes, based on the aPriori cost technology and data, production volume, outcome geometry, material, manufacturing process, and location of manufacture.
When selecting materials in the Study Materials dialog, the calculator icon indicates that costs can be estimated for that material. Certain geometry, such as small pockets or tight radiuses, may increase the production time which results in higher cost estimates. For Additive, check if your model size satisfies the build volume limit of commercially available machines.

Specifies the angle, or amount of slope, given to walls, cores, and other parts of the die cavity to allow for easy ejection of the casting from the die. The draft angle is also known as the draft.
All die cast surfaces that are parallel to the opening direction of the die require draft for proper ejection of the casting from the die.
As the alloy cools and shrinks towards the features that for the inside component surfaces, it fits more tightly on the inside casting. Make sure the design of the casting has sufficient draft for easier casting removal.

Specifies the maximum thickness that you anticipate using for the part. Typical wall thicknesses depend on the size of the part, its application, its configuration, and the alloy used.
Minimize wall thickness variations around the casting for better metal flow and complete casting filling. Different wall thicknesses can result in different rates of cooling along the casting walls, and variation in the dimensions of your part.
The solver uses the maximum thickness, in conjunction with other constraints and objectives such as draft angle, ejection direction, stiffness, safety factor and target mass. In some cases, the resultant thickness may exceed the set maximum thickness value, so that other constraints can be satisfied.

Specifies the minimum thickness that you anticipate using for the part. Keep the wall as thin as possible to meet the functional requirements. Typical wall thicknesses depend on the size of the part, its application, its configuration, and the alloy used.
Minimize wall thickness variations around the casting for better metal flow and complete casting filling. Different wall thicknesses can result in different rates of cooling along the casting walls, and variation in the dimensions of your part.
The solver uses the minimum thickness, in conjunction with other constraints and objectives such as draft angle, ejection direction, stiffness, safety factor and target mass. In some cases, the resultant thickness may undercut the set minimum thickness value, so that other constraints can be satisfied.

Specifies a substitutive diameter of the machine head. It is a diameter of a simplified head that contains the shaft and holder.
